challengeName: Fun Series December - Learning Data Science - Forecasting
detailedRequirements:
.

Challenge Overview

This challenges requires you to look for a trend in a series of noisy data sets and then forecast the region in which the secret next points in each series are most likely to occur.

We have again tried to choose a problem accessible to beginners, while also being flexible enough for more experienced users to experiment.

Please Note: This challenge is for fun, learning, and experience. No prizes will be awarded for completing the challenge.

The Challenge

You are given a file containing 200 distinct sets of 100 (x,y) pairs of points with x = 1,2,…,100. For each set of points, you are to define a quadrilateral region that your forecast is likely to contain a high density of the next 100 points x = 101,102,…,200 in the data set.

The continuation points x = 101,102,…,200 in each set have been generated using the same rule as the first 100 points. The continuation points are being kept secret and will be used to score the submissions.

The data is provided in a CSV file with three numeric columns:

  • The Data Set Number, an Integer from 1 to 200

  • The X value for the given data set where x is one of the sequence 1,2,…,100

  • The Y value for the given data set (floating point numbers including generated noise)

The data set contains 20,001 rows, including an initial row of header values.

Forums

Forums can be accessed here (Login required, to access the forums)

Scoring

For each data set, every point in the continuation of the series that is within the quadrilateral you specified for that series will increase your score by 1,000 units. Your score for each data set will also be decreased by 2.5 times the total area of your quadrilateral.

The minimum score for a dataset will be 0.

Your overall score will be your total score for all the data sets divided by 200.

We provide an example of R code to score a data set below.

Generating a Data Set

First, we will explain how to build a data series modeled after those in the challenge data set. As in the October data science challenge, we generate a data series by selecting a straight line and then adding gaussian noise to the y values.

 
set.seed(2901)

randomLine <- function() {
  # y = mx + b
  m <- runif(1, min=-1, max=1)   # uniformly distributed
  b <- runif(1, min=-50, max=50) # uniformly distributed
  c(m=m, b=b)
}

par(mar=c(.5,.5,2.0,.5)) # shrink default graph margins
plot(c(0,200),c(-200,200), axes=F, frame.plot=T,
     main="Example Random Lines",
     xlab="",ylab="",type="n")

plotRandomLine <- function() {
  line <- randomLine();
  abline(line[2], line[1], col=rgb(0,0,0,.25))
  NULL
}

ingore <- replicate(25, plotRandomLine())
 

The lines are not arbitrarily distributed, since both the slope and the intercepts are constrained. You are permitted to use this information as part of your solution. If you do, please share a forum posting on your reasoning.

In many data science applications, we would have to worry about the validity of the hypotheses that the underlying relationship is linear and that the noise is normally distributed. For the fun series we simplifying by generating data so that we know both the underlying function and the type of noise.

Let’s see how to generate a data set for this challenge, including (1) the line used to generate the points, (2) the public shared points, and (3) the points that will be kept secret for scoring.

 
generatePoints <- function() {
  aLine <- randomLine()
  x <- 1:200
  y <- aLine['m'] * x + aLine['b']
  ynoisy <- y + rnorm(length(x), sd=75)
  list(pts=cbind(x=x, y=ynoisy), line=aLine)
}

set.seed(2904)

testData <- generatePoints()


plotPublicPoints <- function(testData) {
  
  pts <- testData$pts
  public <- pts[1:100,]
  secret <- pts[101:200,]
  
  par(mar=c(.5,.5,.5,.5)) # shrink default graph margins
  plot(public[,'x'], public[,'y'], ylim=c(-300,300), xlim=c(1,200), 
       pch=19, cex=0.2, col='blue', axes=F, frame.plot=T)
}

plotPublicPoints(testData)

 We next plot the public points in blue and the secret points in red. We will also fit a blue line to the public points, a red line to the private points, and a black line for the ground truth we used to generate all the points.

plotPointsAndLines <- function(testData) {
  
  pts <- testData$pts
  public <- pts[1:100,]
  secret <- pts[101:200,]
  
  plotPublicPoints(testData)
  points(secret[,'x'], secret[,'y'], pch=19, cex=.2, col='red')
  
  publicfit <- lm(y ~ x, data.frame(public))
  abline(coef(publicfit)[1], coef(publicfit)[2], col='blue')
  
  secretfit <- lm(y ~ x, data.frame(secret))
  abline(coef(secretfit)[1], coef(secretfit)[2], col='red')
  
  abline(testData$line['b'], testData$line['m'])
}

plotPointsAndLines(testData)

The three lines demonstrate that the least squares fit for the public points, the least squares fit for the secret points, and the overall source line used to generate the points do not match. (The random seed was chosen to highlight these differences.)

If you are confused by the notion of the ground truth line differing from the lines fit to the noisy samples, you might want to consider the challenge statement from the October fun series match. We also have a PDF of plots of all the solutions submitted for each of the 20 data series in the October Challenge.. In the PDF, the ground truth line is in red and the various strategies for fitting a line are plotted in transparent gray. Darker black lines indicate coinciding solutions. Please feel free to ask questions in the forums!

Note that whereas solutions of the October Challenge were scored against the ground truth line, for this challenge the solutions are scored against the actual locations of the secret red points.

A Sample Solution

As a sample solution to this problem, we will calculate the sample standard deviation of the noisy public points and then define a parallelogram that extends 1 standard deviation above and below the line fit to the public points.

 
sampleSolution <- function(testData) {
  
  pts <- testData$pts
  public <- pts[1:100,]
  secret <- pts[101:200,]
  
  stddev <- sd(public[,'y'])
  publicfit <- lm(y ~ x, data.frame(public))

  y101 <- coef(publicfit)[2] * 101 + coef(publicfit)[1]
  y200 <- coef(publicfit)[2] * 200 + coef(publicfit)[1]
  quadMatrix <- cbind(x=c(101, 101, 200, 200), 
                    y=c(y101-stddev, y101+stddev, y200+stddev, y200-stddev))
}

plotPointsAndLines(testData)
quadMatrix <- sampleSolution(testData)
polygon(quadMatrix[,'x'], quadMatrix[,'y'], col=rgb(0,0,1,0.1), border='blue')

Of course, when running on the challenge dataset, the red points will be kept secret. A solution for the given set of points will consist of a polygon appropriately positioned to catch a high density of the red points.

 

Scoring the Solution

Our first step in scoring a solution is to calculate the area of the quadrilateral. We’ll use Varignon’s Theorem and ignore the orientation of the quadrilateral by taking the absolute value of the results:

 
# m is a 4x2 matrix, with x values in col1 and y values in col2
areaQuad <- function(m){
  x <- m[,1]
  y <- m[,2]
  ans <- abs((x[3] - x[1])*(y[4] - y[2]) - (x[4] - x[2])*(y[3] - y[1]))/2
  names(ans) <- 'area'
  ans
}

quadMatrix <- sampleSolution(testData)
areaQuad(quadMatrix)
 ## area 
## 13924.48

Next we must identify which points are inside our quadrilateral. We’ll use a slight varition of a general algorithm for identifying whether a point is interior to a polygon.

 
# TRUE if the point (px,py) is interior to or on the border of the polygon
# defined by the x coordinates in vx and y's in vy.
pinpoly <- function(px, py, vx, vy) {
  
  cnt <- length(vx)
  ans <- FALSE
  j <- cnt # first compare is between 1st and last vertices
  
  for (i in 1:cnt) {
    
    # when py is on the projection of the side on the y axis
    if ((vy[i] > py) != (vy[j] > py)) {
      
      # the x value of intersection of current poly side with a horizontal
      # line through the current point.
      xintersect <- (vx[j]-vx[i]) * (py-vy[i]) / (vy[j]-vy[i]) + vx[i]
      
      # any point directly on a side will always be interior.
      if (px == xintersect) {
        ans <- TRUE
        break
      }
      # otherwise we're scanning for odd number of sides intersecting
      # to the right
      if (px < xintersect) {
        ans <- !ans
      }
    }
    j <- i
  }
  return(ans)
}

# Given a series of points with x values in vector ptsx and y values
# in ptsy, answer a vector of booleans specifying whether the corresponding
# point is in the polygon vx, vy.  Not the most efficient approach in R,
# but easier to understand and easier to translate into another langauge.
ptsinpoly <- function(ptsx, ptsy, vx, vy) {
  ans <- rep(NA, length(ptsx))
  for(i in 1:length(ptsx)) {
    ans[i] <- pinpoly(ptsx[i], ptsy[i], vx, vy)
  }
  return(ans)
}

 

There are several R packages that include point-in-polygon functions. The function here will get you running in R without any library dependencies, while handling the point-on-boundary case the way that this challenge requires. It should also be easily translatable into other languages.

Next we will use the area and number of points to calculate a score. We’ll plot all the points, render our polygon, and, to help verify our point-in-poly logic, draw a circle around each exterior point:

 
# Given a series of public and secret points and a 
# quadirlateral region, plot the region, circle the 
# exterior points, and return the score for the 
# given quadrilateral.
score <- function(testData, quadMatrix, plotResults=T) {
  
  pts <- testData$pts
  public <- pts[1:100,]
  secret <- pts[101:200,]
  
  area <- areaQuad(quadMatrix)
  classifyPts <- ptsinpoly(secret[,'x'], secret[,'y'], 
                             quadMatrix[,'x'], quadMatrix[,'y'])
  
  # drop=FALSE prevents single row selection from being 
  # reduced to a vector.
  exteriorPts <- secret[classifyPts == F,, drop=FALSE]  

  if (plotResults) {
    plotPointsAndLines(testData)
    polygon(
      quadMatrix[,'x'], quadMatrix[,'y'], col=rgb(0,0,1,0.1), border='blue')
    points(exteriorPts[,'x'], exteriorPts[,'y'], col='red')
    # readline("<RET> to continue.")
  }
  
  score <- max(0, 1000 * sum(classifyPts) - 2.5 * area)
  
  ans <- c(area, sum(classifyPts), score)
  names(ans) <- c('area', 'hits', 'score')
  ans
}

score(testData, sampleSolution(testData))

##     area     hits    score 
## 13924.48    63.00 28188.80 

The polygon in our sample solution includes 63 of the secret data points, so we scored 1000 * 63 - 2.5 * 13924.48 = 28188.8 points for this prediction.

Our sample polygon is a parallelogram. This is not required. A solution can be any non-crossing quadrilateral.
finalSubmissionGuidelines:
Submitting Your Solution

For this challenge you may submit a solution multiple times. We will score submissions at least once per week and post a leaderboard of intermediate results. You may review the scores on the leaderboard and choose to submit a new solution for the next scoring. Only your most recent submission will count for the next scoring.

The answer you submit should be formatted as a nine column CSV. Do not include a header row. There is no need for quotes around the values. The columns should contain:

  • Column 1: The Data Set Number

  • Column 2: The X value of Vertex1

  • Column 3: The Y value of Vertex1

  • Column 4: The X value of Vertex2

  • Column 5: The Y value of Vertex2

  • Column 6: The X value of Vertex3

  • Column 7: The Y value of Vertex3

  • Column 8: The X value of Vertex4

  • Column 9: The Y value of Vertex4

Be careful not to provide a crossed quadrilateral (i.e. two triangular regions). To avoid this, always define Vertex1 as the lower left corner, Vertex2 as the upper left corner, Vertex3 as the upper right corner, Vertex4 as the lower right corner of your quadrilateral region.

Each time you submit an answer, we request that you also submit a brief description of the technique(s) you used. You can submit this explanation by including a short comment in a “method.txt” file in the zip file that contains your solution file.
